INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Lie on your back with your lower back lightly pressed into the floor.
2. Brace your abs and lift your shoulders or legs only as far as the brace holds.
3. Move with control through the prescribed range — heel touch, toe tap, or leg movement.
4. Keep your lower back in contact with the floor for the whole set.
5. Lower under control; do not let the legs or shoulders crash down.
6. Breathing: Exhale as you contract the abs. Inhale as you return to the start. Breathe steadily — do not hold your breath.
7. Form check: If your lower back lifts off the floor, reduce the range.
8. Form check: Move from the abs — do not yank the neck or swing the legs.
9. The Alternate Heel Touches mainly trains your Abdominals (rectus abdominis), Obliques (external and internal obliques). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'floor_core',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=floor_core] NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.9; McGill, Low Back Disorders 2nd ed. — trunk / core training$instr$, '2085-2026-05-18'
