  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM public.exercise_instruction_backup
                  WHERE id = 'e7d3a706-e53e-485c-aa59-d6fe40562133');
UPDATE public.exercise_library SET instructions = $instr$1. Stand tall holding the weight at your sides (or in front), arms straight and relaxed.
2. Brace your core; your arms are just hooks, they do not lift.
3. Lift your shoulders straight UP toward your ears.
4. Pause briefly at the top and squeeze the upper traps.
5. Lower under control to a full stretch.
6. Breathing: Inhale before the shrug. Exhale as you lift the shoulders up. Inhale on the way down.
7. Form check: Move straight up and down — rolling the shoulders adds no benefit and stresses the joint.
8. Form check: Keep the chin level; do not crane the neck forward.
9. The Barbell Jump Shrug mainly trains your Quadriceps (Quadriceps Femoris), Glutes (Gluteus Maximus). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$ WHERE id = 'e7d3a706-e53e-485c-aa59-d6fe40562133';

INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Hinge forward at the hips with a flat back, or set up chest-supported on an incline bench.
2. Let the weights hang straight down with a soft, fixed bend in the elbows.
3. Brace your core and keep your head in line with your spine.
4. Raise the weights out to the sides, squeezing the shoulder blades lightly together.
5. Lower under control, keeping tension on the rear delts throughout.
6. Breathing: Inhale before the rep. Exhale as you raise the weights out. Inhale on the controlled descent.
7. Form check: Lead with the elbows and stop at shoulder height.
8. Form check: Keep the movement at the shoulder — do not bend the elbows and turn it into a row.
9. The Barbell Rear Delt Raise mainly trains your Deltoids (Posterior Deltoids). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'rear_delt_fly',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=rear_delt_fly] NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.13 — single-joint resistance technique$instr$, '2085-2026-05-18'
