   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Set up with the weight at mid-chest, feet planted and core braced.
2. Position your elbows tucked at roughly 45 degrees from your torso.
3. Set your shoulder blades down and back against the bench or floor.
4. Press the weight away from your chest until your arms are nearly straight.
5. Lower under control back to the chest, stopping just short of a hard lockout.
6. Breathing: Inhale as the weight lowers and brace. Exhale as you press the weight up. Reset the breath between reps.
7. Form check: Keep the shoulder blades set — do not let them round forward.
8. Form check: Press in a smooth line; do not let the elbows flare wide.
9. The Dumbbell Lying On Floor Chest Press mainly trains your Chest (Pectoralis Major). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'chest_press',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=chest_press] NSCA ESSC 4th ed. ch.13; NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.13 — horizontal pressing$instr$, '2085-2026-05-18'
