INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Stand tall with a slight knee bend, a weight in each hand at your sides.
2. Keep a soft, fixed bend in the elbows of about 10 to 15 degrees.
3. Brace your core and keep your torso still — do not lean back.
4. Raise the weights out to the sides until your arms reach shoulder height.
5. Lower under control to the start, resisting the weight the whole way down.
6. Breathing: Inhale before the raise. Exhale as you lift the weights to shoulder height. Inhale on the controlled descent.
7. Form check: Lead with the elbows, not the hands, and keep the wrists neutral.
8. Form check: Stop at shoulder height — going higher shifts work off the side delts.
9. The Laying Lateral Raise mainly trains your Shoulders (Lateral Deltoids). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'lateral_raise',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=lateral_raise] NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.13 — single-joint resistance technique$instr$, '2085-2026-05-18'
