INSERT INTO public.exercise_instruction_backup
  (id, source_table, old_instructions, new_instructions, movement_class,
   source_citation, rewrite_batch)
SELECT id, 'exercise_library', instructions, $instr$1. Anchor a band at elbow height, or lie on your side holding a light dumbbell.
2. Pin the working elbow to your side, bent at 90 degrees.
3. Keeping the elbow glued in place, rotate your forearm outward.
4. Move only as far as the shoulder rotates freely — a small range is normal.
5. Return slowly under control to the start.
6. Breathing: Inhale before the rep. Exhale as you rotate outward. Inhale on the controlled return.
7. Form check: Keep the elbow pinned to your ribs the entire time.
8. Form check: Use very light resistance — this trains rotator-cuff control, it is not a strength lift.
9. The Resistance Band Standing External Rotation mainly trains your Rotator Cuff (Infraspinatus, Teres Minor). If you are newer to it, start light and add load only once the movement feels controlled, and on heavier sets end the set when your form or brace breaks down rather than grinding out a risky rep.$instr$, 'external_rotation',
  $instr$[rule | engine=exercise_instruction_copy.dart | class=external_rotation] NASM EPFT 6th ed. ch.13 — single-joint resistance technique$instr$, '2085-2026-05-18'
